      Here you put everything inside &lt;div&gt;'s which you can give the class container or container fluid.
      Where class="container-fluid" means that the div will be using the whole width of the screen of the device.
</pre>

  <pre>
    <h3><a id="grid">GRID</a></h3>
      After adding the CDN code to your project you can start-off by adding code to the body.
      Here you put everything inside &lt;div&gt;'s which you can give the class container or container fluid.
      Where class="container-fluid" means that the div will be using the whole width of the screen of the device.
      The Bootstrap GRID system consists of 12 columns which you can group tigether just as you seem fit.
      There are 4 classes you use when using the GRID system:
        xs - extra small => for phones
        sm - small => for tablets
        md - medium => for normail desktops and laptops
        xl - extra large => for larger desktops like 27 inch iMac
      For making a 3 column (GRID) layout website you need to group 3 x 4 columns together.
      You do this (inside the "body") like so:
      &lt;div class="container-fluid"&gt;   => <em>fluid to make it take up the whole screen</em>.
        &lt;h1&gt;3 column layout&lt;h1&gt;
        &lt:div class="row"&gt;  => <em>you give the created columns the class 'row'</em>.
          &lt;div class="col-md-4" style="background-color: #ff9999"&gt;Left&lt;/div&gt;   => <em>col means column, md is the medium size,</em>
          &lt;div class="col-md-4" style="background-color: #99ccff"&gt;Middle&lt;/div&gt;                      <em>4 is the amount of columns</em>.
          &lt;div class="col-md-4" style="background-color: #00cc99"&gt;Right&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
  </pre>

  <pre>
    <h3><a id="styling">Text Styling</a></h3>
      To highlight text you can use the style tag mark like so: &lt;mark&gt;some text&lt;/mark&gt;
      *<span class="line_alink">Blockquote</span> you can use for styling 'quotes' like so:
      &lt;blockquote&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;You can do anything, but not everything.&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;footer&gt;David Allen&lt;/footer&gt;
      &lt;/blockquote&gt;
      *<span class="line_alink">List</span>, to make a list you do this:
      &lt;p&gt;Things to do when you're bored&lt;/p&gt;
      &lt;dl&gt;
        &lt;dt&gt;Indoors&lt;/dt&gt;
          &lt;dd&gt;Take a nap&lt;/dd&gt;
          &lt;dd&gt;Watch Netflix&lt;/dd&gt;
        &lt;dt&gt;Outdoors&lt;/dt&gt;
          &lt;dd&gt;- Go back inside&lt;/dd&gt;
        &lt;/dl&gt;
      *<span class="line_alink">Multi-line code</span>, for this you best use the 'pre' tag.
      It works like this:
      &lt;p&gt;for multi-line code you use pre tags&lt;/p&gt;
      &lt;pre&gt;
        for n in range(101):
        if(n % 4 is 0):
        print(n)
      &lt;/pre&gt;
      *<span class="line_alink">Userweight</span>: &lt;p&gt; to set the users weight use &lt;code&gt;setUserWeight(374);&lt;/code&gt; with an integer.&lt;/p&gt;
        => <em>gives red letter with a white background</em>.
      *<span class="line_alink">Keyboard &lt;kbd&gt; input</span> can be marked this way: &lt;p class="one">This is suppost to be keyboard input &lt;kbd&gt;ctrl+alt+del&lt;/kbd&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
       => <em>gives a black background with white letters</em>.
       *<span class="line_alink">Color classes:</span>: are build in colors in bootstrap that let you know if the part in a form has been
       filled out correctly (text color goes green) or muted (text color goes light grey) or wrong (text color goes red).
       This works like this:
       &lt;h4&gt;Build in color classes&lt;h4&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-muted"&gt;Text muted&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-success"&gt;Form filled out correctly&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-danger"&gt;Danger text&lt;/p&gt;
        You can also use these for background colors like so:
        &lt;p class="bg-danger"&gt;Danger text&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p class="bg-success"&gt;Success text&lt;/p&gt;
  </pre>

  <pre>
    <h3><a id="tables">Tables</a></h3>
      Three examples of 'Tables' in Bootstrap, &lt;table class="table"&gt;, &lt;table class="table table-condensed"&gt; and
      &lt;table class="table table-stripped"&gt;.
      class table is the standard table, condensed is a table with less padding than the standard an the stripped <table>
      has each other row with a tint for clearity.
      Example:
      &lt;div class="container"&gt;
        &lt;h2&gt;Simple table&lt;/h2&gt;
        &lt;table class="table"&gt;  => <em>also for &lt;table class="table table-condensed"&gt; and for</em>
          &lt;thead&gt;                          <em>&lt;table class="table table-stripped"&gt;</em>
            &lt;tr&gt;
              &lt;th&gt;Name&lt;/th&gt;
              &lt;th&gt;Age&lt;/th&gt;
              &lt;th&gt;Points&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;/tr&gt;
          &lt;/thead&gt;
          &lt;tbody&gt;
            &lt;tr&gt;
              &lt;td&gt;Frank de Wolf&lt;/td&gt;
